there listening. I'll throw it with another stat that blew me away. The PSF JetBrains Python

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:57.499
Developer Survey asks all the respondents, how long have you been programming as a professional

00:11:58.120 --> 00:12:00.600
software developer in any language, not just Python.

00:12:02.060 --> 00:12:05.040
And the 50% of the respondents said less than two years.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:06.660
Right, right.

00:12:06.900 --> 00:12:08.460
So a lot of the people out there listening

00:12:08.850 --> 00:12:10.920
maybe don't even know what Anaconda is,

00:12:11.050 --> 00:12:13.300
even though it's very well known within the Python space.

00:12:13.720 --> 00:12:15.820
Give us a bit about what you guys are up to these days.

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:18.920
Yeah, so we started, I think,

00:12:18.970 --> 00:12:20.620
probably best known as the providers

00:12:20.730 --> 00:12:22.380
of the eponymous Anaconda distribution

00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:25.100
and the installers for the various packages.

00:12:26.600 --> 00:12:43.020
And really our bread and butter is building out, you know, the Python packages, maintaining a kind of curated repository and really selling access to that to commercial businesses that want to actually have a vendor back, vendor supported source of Python packages.

00:12:43.700 --> 00:12:48.460
And for most Python packages, I mean, there's many people in the world who are very happy pip installing off PyPI.

00:12:48.900 --> 00:12:49.540
Things work great.

00:12:50.020 --> 00:12:59.040
But when you get into some of the more numerical or maybe GPU intensive packages, the way it gets built is enormously important and can sometimes be very, very challenging.

00:12:59.700 --> 00:13:06.760
So when we started Anaconda over 10 years ago, it was actually very, very hard to get those pre-built binaries installed.

00:13:07.220 --> 00:13:07.900
Now it's a little bit easier.

00:13:08.120 --> 00:13:12.660
People are rolling a lot of libraries into these big fat wheels from 5PI.

00:13:13.120 --> 00:13:14.960
And that can work pretty well in some cases.

00:13:15.040 --> 00:13:16.820
In some cases, it fails catastrophically.

00:13:16.880 --> 00:13:19.680
But what we do is we provide enterprise support.

00:13:20.120 --> 00:13:36.740
We provide also just a validated and secure open source supply chain around these really important binary artifacts that then become deployed into Docker containers that become then the runtime for machine learning and data processing for very sensitive customer data and things like that.

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:42.480
So we have a model that's very similar to what Red Hat did for Linux, where you can get Linux for free.

00:13:42.480 --> 00:13:43.420
You can run the free stuff.

00:13:43.660 --> 00:13:45.940
You can go and pick up packages from the free community repositories.

00:13:46.460 --> 00:13:49.900
but if you're really serious about a business runtime environment and you really want to have

00:13:50.080 --> 00:13:54.920
a throat to throttle, so to speak, if something is not quite right, then you go and you go pay

00:13:55.040 --> 00:13:58.200
Red Hat for the annual subscription. And so we have very similar business model around that.

00:13:59.220 --> 00:14:03.900
We made the Conda Package Manager, but to be very clear, the Conda Package Manager is an open

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:09.400
source project. So we put that into the open source and have a community around that. The

00:14:09.500 --> 00:14:13.539
Conda Forge community is the package build community around that. We host the repositories

00:14:13.560 --> 00:14:19.080
there but those are free for everyone to use so we really have been you know from a from a

00:14:19.080 --> 00:14:23.340
business standpoint that's a bread and butter working with things like microsoft excel and

00:14:23.420 --> 00:14:28.400
working with things like snowflake to really embed uh polished python run times inside those

00:14:28.520 --> 00:14:33.440
computational environments that's something we started doing a few years back um this year i

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:37.700
think for the most part people's experiences of anaconda are have not changed too much just kind

00:14:37.700 --> 00:14:41.000
of packaging whatever but there are a lot of things kind of happening behind the scenes right

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:46.320
So we did, for instance, the Python and Excel stuff, which we'll be talking about later, is a huge thing that we're very excited about.

00:14:46.700 --> 00:14:50.980
But then we've also been pushing forward on our perspectives on AI.

00:14:51.240 --> 00:14:54.300
So we know that a lot of, like I said earlier, a lot of AI is built on Python.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:15:00.380
A lot of AI relies on having the right packages and software alongside the models and whatnot.

00:15:01.100 --> 00:15:09.480
And we have a particular belief that the models will get smaller and more people want to run these models locally or close to their sensors and their data.

00:15:10.100 --> 00:15:15.240
They're not going to want to upload these into the cloud, or it's not going to be feasible because they have a lot of video streams from many different kinds of sensors.

00:15:15.870 --> 00:15:22.020
And they're going to want to have a solid software stack to run these models that they need to update and fine tune.

00:15:23.100 --> 00:15:31.520
And so really looking at ourselves as a provider of that level of the software stack for people, that's kind of what we're orienting towards.

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:36.820
So we released a product called AI Navigator, which people can go and use to download models.

00:15:37.740 --> 00:15:39.220
We host the model repository.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:42.040
So we have a curated set of quantized models that we're hosting.

00:15:42.640 --> 00:15:43.960
And so people who, you know,

00:15:43.970 --> 00:15:47.300
one of the things that we got from our enterprise customers quite a bit was,

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:50.220
hey, we like using your enterprise software package repository.

00:15:50.350 --> 00:15:53.760
We love that it's, you know, has your stamp of security approval on it.

00:15:54.050 --> 00:15:56.100
But do you have anything like that for models?

00:15:56.450 --> 00:15:59.840
Because we just right now download stuff off Hugging Face and that's kind of okay.

00:16:00.350 --> 00:16:03.460
But like, you know, like we don't really know who quantized this.

00:16:03.460 --> 00:16:05.740
That's running arbitrary code off the internet.

00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:06.440
How could it go wrong?

00:16:07.400 --> 00:16:16.040
And, you know, not to throw shade on any of that because an open innovation is great, but people do feel like, you know, we need something in between there.

00:16:16.100 --> 00:16:18.760
So we have both our AI navigator, which lets you run models locally.

00:16:19.320 --> 00:16:23.700
It's similar to like if you use like an LM studio or something like that, it's a nice way to sort of get all this stuff running locally.

00:16:24.260 --> 00:16:41.400
But then you also get a, we have our model repo, which is kind of right now in an alpha stage, alpha beta stage for people to, if they want to run that on-prem, they can then have an on-prem model repo and IT can actually have a view on what's getting deployed in various places.

