00:19:27.210 --> 00:19:31.600
I have the great misfortune of having wandered all five or six dimensions in my career, but

00:19:31.720 --> 00:19:33.860
most people experience only two or three of those dimensions.

00:19:34.540 --> 00:19:36.560
So for their perspective, it could just be this simple.

00:19:36.640 --> 00:19:37.780
Or why don't I just do that?

00:19:38.080 --> 00:19:42.500
I just homebrew my dependencies or I just use RPM to install these base libraries.

00:19:42.660 --> 00:19:45.780
And then I pip install these other things in a Docker and I'm done, right?

00:19:46.400 --> 00:19:56.060
But what we have to do as maintainers and also as people who kind of cater to a broad tens of millions large user land is we have to account for all six of those dimensions.

00:19:56.620 --> 00:19:58.720
And sometimes they're not obvious to people, right?

00:19:59.500 --> 00:20:18.160
So in the case of wheels, to come back to the discussion about wheels and Barry's proposal there, the issue that many maintainers have with wheels, especially if they're maintainers of libraries that have a lot of C dependencies, is that you're stuck between a devil and a hard place, or a rock and a hard place.

00:20:18.740 --> 00:20:33.540
And so you have to decide, do I bundle all these dependencies in, in which case I own the compatibility issues and I own the security issues that come with having bundled in a bunch of C libraries or C++ libraries?

00:20:34.230 --> 00:20:38.540
If I don't bundle them in, then users are kind of stuck trying to install this thing, right?

00:20:39.260 --> 00:20:43.820
And so what we find is that for some libraries, it's okay.

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:46.200
For other libraries, it's very difficult.

00:20:46.280 --> 00:20:51.420
and the Python ecosystem, I think, ultimately still does not have a great solution to this.

00:20:51.630 --> 00:20:59.700
And Wheels, as the way that the PyPA and the pip maintainers and other people we've talked to over the years,

00:21:00.240 --> 00:21:03.640
they really want to think of the packaging problem as a Python packaging problem.

00:21:04.460 --> 00:21:09.360
And with Conda, because it was built, it was purpose-built for the scientific Python ecosystem,

00:21:09.980 --> 00:21:12.860
we knew from the outset that our problem was bigger than Python.

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:16.440
In fact, most of the problem was packaging stuff that wasn't Python.

00:21:16.850 --> 00:21:18.700
The Python bits were trivial almost, right?

00:21:19.170 --> 00:21:21.620
But it's the, you know, what version of Clang?

00:21:21.800 --> 00:21:23.360
What C++ ABI do you use?

00:21:23.520 --> 00:21:25.440
What version of this do you link?

00:21:25.450 --> 00:21:27.720
What flags do you turn on when you invoke GCC here?

00:21:28.140 --> 00:21:30.900
When you go and you compile something and all of that,

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:32.740
not only are you including all the C libraries,

00:21:33.360 --> 00:21:35.720
you're also inheriting all of the design,

00:21:36.240 --> 00:21:41.420
sorry, the configuration options of the build tool chain at compile time.

00:21:41.920 --> 00:21:46.240
It's an enormously complex thing that ends up getting wrapped up into a single wheel, right?

00:21:46.940 --> 00:21:50.760
So with conda, these are represented explicit dependencies with feature flags.

00:21:50.860 --> 00:21:56.360
And you can then sort of do this package dependency solver, which of course is good and bad.

00:21:56.500 --> 00:21:59.300
If the ecosystem gets too big, the solve takes too long.

00:21:59.760 --> 00:22:03.960
But then if you don't do that solve, then you just run into stochastic and irreproducible installations.

00:22:04.760 --> 00:22:05.560
So what do you do, right?

00:22:06.080 --> 00:22:09.620
So this proposal, specifically about this proposal that Barry's put out there,

00:22:10.200 --> 00:22:14.360
This is, I think, meant to address, and he works now at NVIDIA,

00:22:14.960 --> 00:22:20.140
and people who've had to deal with GPU packages know that the CUDA libraries can be quite large.

00:22:20.600 --> 00:22:23.940
They get pretty big, and they are somewhat of a tax on the hosting infrastructure,

00:22:24.110 --> 00:22:26.440
on the CDN there for PyPI.

00:22:27.160 --> 00:22:33.520
And so the limit that PyPI has imposed makes it difficult for them to kind of have increasingly larger packages

00:22:33.860 --> 00:22:36.140
and all these like nightly bills that they want to upload.

00:22:36.660 --> 00:22:39.180
So this proposal is, can we split this out?

00:22:39.720 --> 00:22:44.220
these rim files and so we put a placeholder in place on pypi and then put the actual package over

00:22:44.400 --> 00:22:51.960
here right right if nvidia wants to ship a 400 meg pip installable package let them host it

00:22:53.240 --> 00:22:58.120
right something like that right that's right and so this gets to one of the demons i mentioned

00:22:58.360 --> 00:23:04.280
which is that a repository is not the same as a distribution and it's not the same as an ftp site

00:23:04.280 --> 00:23:10.000
or Dropbox. These are actually very different things. And I have not actually commented

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:14.680
officially on this on the discourse at all. I've had some private conversations with people,

00:23:15.160 --> 00:23:20.400
but I might as well, since you asked, my thought is that this is not a bad idea,

00:23:21.020 --> 00:23:28.560
but the challenge is we are going to go down a path essentially of having to solve the CAP theorem.

00:23:29.320 --> 00:23:33.000
What I mean by that is if you view PyPI, what is PyPI?

00:23:33.340 --> 00:23:35.440
Is it a Dropbox where anyone can just upload whatever?

00:23:36.580 --> 00:23:36.720
Okay.

00:23:37.380 --> 00:23:45.680
But the problem there is if someone installs something today and they try to install again tomorrow or two weeks from now, they're going to generally want the same kinds of things.

00:23:46.700 --> 00:23:55.260
And if it's just a Dropbox, then no one is responsible for providing a stable snapshot of what points to what and what is what even.

00:23:55.900 --> 00:24:01.480
Because in the space of even an hour or two on something as large as PyPI, you can have updates.

00:24:01.590 --> 00:24:03.680
You can have updates of versions with different build strings.

00:24:04.560 --> 00:24:08.860
People can yank a file because, oh, my God, I bought the build on that and so on and so forth.

00:24:09.380 --> 00:24:11.500
So if you view it just as a Dropbox, that's okay.

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:18.700
But then all the work of consistency and reproducibility gets foisted onto the install tools, the client side tools.

00:24:19.080 --> 00:24:23.120
Whether it's uv, whether it's pip, whether it's Poetry, PyM, you name it.

00:24:23.260 --> 00:24:25.900
Patch, PDM, Poetry, all these wonderful tools.

00:24:26.220 --> 00:24:27.400
Anaconda, too, I should put that out there, right?

00:24:27.980 --> 00:24:29.480
Everyone is trying to solve this problem,

00:24:29.870 --> 00:24:35.580
and the question is, is the repository host going to solve the atomic sort of state view,

00:24:35.690 --> 00:24:37.940
or is the client going to have to piece it together somehow?

00:24:39.120 --> 00:24:41.900
And then the reason I mentioned the CAP theorem is if you say,

00:24:42.110 --> 00:24:46.780
okay, we should pretend that it's somewhat of a stable repository, not just a Dropbox,

00:24:47.260 --> 00:24:52.620
but as a repository, that means that there's a snapshot of things at a state in time, the metadata.

00:24:52.660 --> 00:25:01.040
Well, okay, but if you allow for some of these packages to be hosted over here, now you have a distributed database. You have a distributed object database.

00:25:02.280 --> 00:25:03.240
Massively distributed.

00:25:03.540 --> 00:25:16.200
Massively distributed. And NVIDIA, obviously, as a trillion-dollar company, can keep up a CDN, okay? But they cannot avoid net splits. They cannot avoid a backhoe in Reston nuking a fiber line somewhere, right?

00:25:16.240 --> 00:25:24.800
You cannot avoid the kinds of things that happen that cause a distributed network database to suffer consistency problems.

00:25:25.430 --> 00:25:38.880
So now someone building a Docker, and when you're looking at something as important as the CUDA-oriented libraries, the RAPIDS libraries, these really important foundational GPU libraries, people are pulling these to the tune of thousands and thousands per second.

00:25:39.440 --> 00:25:41.660
So you have got to make sure you're consistent all the time.

00:25:41.740 --> 00:25:47.020
Otherwise, someone's production Docker build falls back on an old version because they couldn't get the most recent one.

00:25:47.450 --> 00:25:50.100
Or in the best case, it times out and complains loudly.

00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:52.960
The worst case, it fails silently and falls back.

00:25:53.390 --> 00:25:57.120
And whatever client-side tool they're using then says, well, I can't get that, so I want to solve this way.

00:25:57.160 --> 00:25:58.280
I'm going to solve this other thing over here.

00:25:58.610 --> 00:26:03.540
They pick up an old version, and now you have whatever reason your model build deployment doesn't work.

00:26:04.380 --> 00:26:09.220
Maybe you picked up a regression equivalent of a bug that you know is fixed in the new one.

00:26:09.230 --> 00:26:11.200
You asked for the new one, but you didn't get the new one.

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:12.460
You didn't get the new one.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:20.860
And so the point is, the reason I cite the cap theorem is at some point, a package hosting site like this has to decide, is it just a Dropbox?

00:26:21.440 --> 00:26:22.220
Is it a repository?

00:26:22.980 --> 00:26:23.080
Right?

00:26:23.520 --> 00:26:31.160
And if it's the latter, then it has to offer an atomic and consistent, verifiable view of the metadata.

00:26:31.980 --> 00:26:34.800
With Conda, we have a thing called repodata.json.

00:26:35.320 --> 00:26:39.540
And it is a big fat file, and it is basically the snapshot of the repository.

00:26:39.740 --> 00:26:40.800
And it is transactional.

00:26:41.320 --> 00:26:44.780
So you get the whole thing and then you can do the solve and say, I want these pieces.

00:26:45.260 --> 00:26:46.100
And then you go get those pieces.

00:26:46.780 --> 00:26:52.860
So from a design standpoint, architect standpoint, it's not that complicated, but it is a different, it's a design difference.

00:26:54.020 --> 00:26:59.720
Then when you think about pip installing off PyPI, it is eager and opportunistic, let's say, right?

00:26:59.860 --> 00:27:03.500
So it goes, tries to install a thing, it grabs that, looks through and says, oh, I need these things.

00:27:03.560 --> 00:27:04.320
It goes and grabs those things.

00:27:04.740 --> 00:27:13.140
And so over the course of a multi-second long or maybe in a multi-minute long install, you don't actually get a consistent view of the repository.

00:27:14.800 --> 00:27:19.420
And so with this, this now says really stresses the question.

00:27:19.460 --> 00:27:28.260
I think what the RIM proposal does, it really forces the question of is PyPI a repository or is it a hosting site?

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.140
Like SunSite thought, yeah, FTP, SunSite.edu back in the day.

00:27:31.460 --> 00:27:33.460
And you just go grab whatever and good luck.

00:27:33.670 --> 00:27:38.540
And all that complexity of consistency is then the responsibility of the client side tools to manage.

00:27:39.360 --> 00:27:41.160
That is the design decision you can make, right?

00:27:42.800 --> 00:27:49.320
Yeah, I hadn't even thought about it from a reproducibility science or even just old applications perspective.

00:27:49.500 --> 00:27:50.680
That's pretty interesting to think about.

00:27:50.900 --> 00:27:52.800
I read this, Pep.

00:27:52.940 --> 00:27:57.340
I don't recall if it talked about a backup

