00:33:47.410 --> 00:33:54.200
So Windows, Excel on Windows, has support for Python in the formula bar.

00:33:54.440 --> 00:34:04.240
So if you have Windows and you run Excel, you can type equals PY in the formula bar and start punching in Python code, multiple line Python code.

00:34:04.660 --> 00:34:08.940
You can refer to cell ranges and it will spill your data frames into the grid.

00:34:09.240 --> 00:34:10.179
You can chart things.

00:34:11.179 --> 00:34:12.340
It's insane that we're here.

00:34:12.600 --> 00:34:13.720
It's amazing that works.

00:34:14.740 --> 00:34:18.040
Now, the way that works is it analyzes your code.

00:34:18.720 --> 00:34:23.440
It actually looks at the range references and the cell reference and everything else, pulls all that data and your code.

00:34:23.879 --> 00:34:27.540
and it sends it over the wire to Azure Confidential Compute,

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:30.280
which is an extra secure, extra lockdown version of Azure.

00:34:31.100 --> 00:34:35.040
And it runs the code there on a customized Anaconda environment

00:34:35.070 --> 00:34:35.700
that we built for that.

00:34:35.710 --> 00:34:39.240
So you have access to a lot of the data tools that you would expect,

00:34:39.600 --> 00:34:40.960
pandas, matplotlib, things like that.

00:34:41.460 --> 00:34:43.419
So you do all that stuff and then it comes back

00:34:44.030 --> 00:34:45.520
and then it sort of renders in the grid.

00:34:46.000 --> 00:34:48.879
So the computational environment doesn't have access

00:34:49.030 --> 00:34:51.738
to your full spreadsheet

00:34:52.280 --> 00:34:54.060
and it also doesn't have access to the internet.

00:34:54.720 --> 00:34:57.480
So there's no risk of data leakage and loss

00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:58.980
and things like that or tampering.

00:34:59.600 --> 00:34:59.980
So in any case-

00:34:59.980 --> 00:35:01.620
It probably also doesn't have access

00:35:01.620 --> 00:35:03.040
to your local file system

00:35:03.040 --> 00:35:04.660
if you've got other things to pull in

