And you've served as a wonderful straight man for me here

00:35:13.180 --> 00:35:15.240
because that is a bit of a limitation.

00:35:15.240 --> 00:35:17.260
So the pluses are number one,

00:35:17.260 --> 00:35:20.638
it's built in and it runs the full-on

00:35:20.720 --> 00:35:24.520
like Anaconda install on the Azure confidential compute.

00:35:25.480 --> 00:35:27.760
So you have access to the bona fide packages and whatnot

00:35:28.380 --> 00:35:29.220
for doing data analysis.

00:35:29.370 --> 00:35:31.320
The downside is there's no access to the internet.

00:35:31.580 --> 00:35:33.580
There's no access to your local file system, things like that.

00:35:33.660 --> 00:35:34.860
You have to sort of load those into Excel

00:35:35.290 --> 00:35:36.340
and then punch that data over.

00:35:37.220 --> 00:35:38.380
So to complement that,

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:41.300
we created this thing that we call the Anaconda Toolbox.

00:35:41.830 --> 00:35:48.358
And so that is actually a WebAssembly-based plugin

00:35:48.360 --> 00:35:55.740
for Microsoft Excel, and it runs on the Mac version of Excel as well, and it runs locally.

00:35:55.890 --> 00:36:03.560
So it is an Anaconda WebAssembly sort of environment hosted inside a plugin for Excel.

00:36:04.330 --> 00:36:12.600
So that then has sort of richer access to things, but it is limited in that only those libraries

00:36:12.610 --> 00:36:15.260
that we cross-compiled into WebAssembly can work in there.

00:36:15.800 --> 00:36:21.860
That being said, you can use sort of a pip install, install pure Python packages into that environment.

